        "text": "In psychology, Jean Piaget used the term assimilation in the context of the cognitive development of children. Here, assimilation describes the integration (fitting) of new information into already existing cognitive schema, perceptions and understanding.\n\nAdaptation, according to Piaget, combines the processes of assimilation and accommodation. While assimilation interprets events in terms of the existing cognitive structure, accommodation changes the cognitive structure to ‘make sense’ of the environment. While assimilation is the basis for accommodation, the processes should be seen as integrated and interactive. Cognition thus could be described as a continuous effort to adapt to the environment by assimilation and accommodation.\n\nThere is no notion of representation or input/output in Piaget’s concept of assimilation. Piaget called his description a ‘genetic epistemology’ emphasizing the generative aspect of the cognitive development of children.\n“The essential functions of the mind consist in understanding and in inventing, in other words, in building up structures by structuring reality.” (Piaget)\nFor cognitive (learning and adaptive) computers, the ability to assimilate and accommodate (abduct from its assimilations) is essential also. Two (or more) assimilative systems interactively operating on each other could enable cognitive computing.\n(see: http://tip.psychology.org/piaget.html, and http://www.oikos.org/Piagethom.htm )\n"
